The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Culture carnival

 To help preserve and propagate rare and vanishing classical, folk and tribal art forms, the Guru Shishya Parampara scheme was introduced by the ministry of culture in its different zonal cultural centres across the country. The system ensures nurturing and development of the skills of young talents, who are trained by acknowledged experts (gurus) in their respective fields. As part of its ongoing initiative to revive dying art forms, Eastern Zonal Cultural Centre hosts Guru Shishya Parampara, a three-day festival with performances by gurus and their shishyas (students) practising the unique, representative art forms of West Bengal, Orissa, Bihar, Jharkhand, Assam and Manipur. The inaugural evening?s programme features folk songs and dances of Bengal. Participants: Naresh Banerjee (raibenshe folk dance), Mahua Mukherjee (goudiya nritya), Amar Pal (folk songs), Purna Das Baul (baul songs) and Bhagaban Das Kumar (Purulia chhau). Tomorrow: Sambalpuri, Mayurbhanj chhau, gotipua and Odissi dances of Orissa, kajri folk songs of Bihar and Seraikella chhau of Jharkhand. The concluding day?s items include kushan, sattriya and bihu dances of Assam, and Manipuri, thang-ta and lai-haraoba dances of Manipur.

 Event: A festival of classical and folk art forms presented by gurus and shishyas

 When: November 7 - 9, 6 pm

 Where: Purbashree, Bharatiyam Cultural Multiplex, IB-201 Salt Lake




